ğŸ§© why Ansible is called agentless: 
Ansible is called â€œagentlessâ€ because â€” unlike many other configuration management tools (like Puppet, Chef, or SaltStack) â€” it does not require any software agent to be installed on the managed nodes.
Ansible inventory syntax:

ğŸ§± 1. Multiple Hosts (Basic Groups)                    

Used to define several servers under specific groups.
This helps you manage similar systems together.

Example:
[webservers]
web1.example.com
web2.example.com
192.168.1.10
192.168.1.11

[dbservers]
db1.example.com
db2.example.com 

ğŸ§± 2. Adding SSH User, Port, and Key
You can define how Ansible connects to each host using connection variables.
Example:
[webservers]
web1 ansible_host=192.168.1.10 ansible_user=ubuntu ansible_port=22 ansible_ssh_private_key_file=~/.ssh/id_rsa
web2 ansible_host=192.168.1.11 ansible_user=ubuntu ansible_port=22 ansible_ssh_private_key_file=~/.ssh/id_rsa
âœ… This tells Ansible which user, port, and SSH key to use when connecting.

ğŸ§± 3. Using Hostname Ranges:
When hosts follow a naming pattern, you can use a range to shorten your file.
Example:
[appservers]
app[1:5].example.com

âœ… This automatically expands to:
app1.example.com
app2.example.com
app3.example.com
app4.example.com
app5.example.com

ğŸ§± 4. Nested Groups (Children Groups):
You can combine multiple groups into a single parent group for easier management.
Example:
[frontend]
web1
web2
[backend]
db1
db2
[production:children]
frontend
backend

The production group now includes all servers from both frontend and backend.

